I. Questions on Your Selected Data

Use the data of your own. Produce the following types of plots and comment on each plot. Plots should be meaningful. If you use the data we used in class, make sure the plots are not the same as the ones in the slides. All plots should have title, caption, appropriate labels on x and y-axis.

library(tidyverse)
df <- read_csv('data/titanic.csv')

  1. Make a plot using face_wrap by one categorical variable (face_wrap(~variable1))

  2. Make a plot using face_wrap by two categorical variables (face_wrap(variable1~variable2))

  3. Make a plot using position ='jitter'.

  4. Make a plot using position ='dodge'.

  5. Make a plot using position ='fill'.

  6. Make a plot using geom_col.

  7. Change the theme of one of your plots.

  8. Save a plot and put a link of the plot to your Github Webpage. To link a plot abc.png you just need to insert the following on the README.md

#1. Make a plot using `face_wrap` by one categorical variable (`face_wrap(~variable1)`)
df %>% 
  ggplot(mapping=aes(x=Age, y=Fare))+ 
  geom_point()+
  facet_wrap(~Sex)+
  labs(x='Age', 
       y = 'Fare', 
       title = 'Scatter Plot of Age and Fare by sex', 
       caption = 'This Plot looks at the price based on age and sex')
## Warning: Removed 177 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

#2. Make a plot using `face_wrap` by two categorical variables (`face_wrap(variable1~variable2)`)
df %>% 
  ggplot(mapping=aes(x=Age, y=Fare))+ 
  geom_point()+
  facet_wrap(Embarked~Sex) +
  labs(x='Age', 
       y = 'Fare', 
       title = 'Scatter Plots of Age and Fare', 
       caption = 'Age and Fare Broken up by Sex and Location of Embarkment')
## Warning: Removed 177 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

#3. Make a plot using `position ='jitter'
df %>% ggplot()+ 
  geom_point(mapping=aes(x=Age, y=Fare, color=Sex), 
             position='jitter')+
  labs(x='Age', 
       y = 'Fare', 
       title = 'Age v. Fare by Sex', 
       caption = 'Age and Fare broken up by the jitter postioning')
## Warning: Removed 177 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

#4. Make a plot using `position ='dodge'
df %>% ggplot()+ 
  geom_bar(mapping=aes(x=Survived, fill=Sex), 
           position = 'dodge') +
  labs(x='Survived', 
       y = 'Count', 
       title = 'Survived Count based on Sex', 
       caption = 'Using the dodge postioning')

#5. Make a plot using `position ='fill'
df %>% ggplot()+ 
  geom_bar(mapping=aes(x=Survived, fill=Sex), 
           position = 'fill') +
  labs(x='Survived', 
       y = 'Count', 
       title = 'Survived Count based on Sex', 
       caption = 'Using the fill postioning')

#6. Make a plot using `geom_col`
df %>% group_by(Embarked) %>% summarise(average_Fare=mean(Fare)) %>%
  ggplot()+ 
  geom_col(mapping=aes(x=Embarked, y=average_Fare)) +
  labs(x='Location of Embarkement', 
       y = 'Average Fare', 
       title = 'Average Fare of Embarkement Locations', 
       caption = 'What the average fare was at each location of embarkement')

#7. Change the theme of one of your plots.
df %>% group_by(Embarked) %>% summarise(average_Fare=mean(Fare)) %>%
  ggplot()+ 
  geom_col(mapping=aes(x=Embarked, y=average_Fare)) +
  theme_dark() +
  labs(x='Location of Embarkement', 
       y = 'Average Fare', 
       title = 'Average Fare of Embarkement Locations', 
       caption = 'the last plot but with the dark theme!')

  1. Since the data seems lack of categorical variables, we will create a few categorical variables for easier visualization. From the Date variable create three categorical variables to record weekdays, months and quarters. You could also create a categorical variable to record the state regions (South, North East, Midwest, West) or other new categorical variables.
library(lubridate)
df$weekday = wday(df$Date)
df$month = month(df$Date)
df$quarter = quarter(df$Date)
